[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating potential issues**\n\nI'm considering the assertion error for timeouts, which doesn't seem great. There's a potential issue with having only public top-level test classes. I'm wondering if the \"legacy.junit3\" package could be considered a library, but probably not. Another concern is regarding dynamic class loading in Native Image; using `rerunTest` with `setLoading(false)` might help. Also, if the environment is headless, rerunning tests requiring JFrame could fail. I might consider avoiding that by using `createUI`, but need to examine it further.\n\n**Exploring headless independence**\n\nI’m thinking about making the rerun test independent of headless settings by using Unsafe to allocate private fields, but that doesn’t seem ideal since direct reflection is forbidden and Unsafe is not great. I wonder if I could use `java.awt.GraphicsEnvironment.isHeadless()`, but that feel like an assumption I can’t skip. There’s also the idea of catching AWTError during the rerun test, particularly if it verifies unsupported cases. If JUnit executes tests in a random order, that could cause issues with the headless setting sticking around.\n\n**Addressing headless issues**\n\nI'm realizing that restoring the property won't reset the cached headless state, which means a later JFrame could still throw a HeadlessException. Since test order isn't guaranteed, I need to avoid setting the global headless to true. Instead, I guess I could configure the `createTestCollector` to throw a controlled exception after `newInstance`, but before the dialog appears. Unfortunately, I can't do that with `SimpleTestCollector`. So maybe I should create a custom TestCollector that sets a flag and returns an empty collection in `collectTests`.\n\n**Considering order execution**\n\nI’m thinking about the order of execution in my tests. I need to incorporate Order, TestMethodOrder, and MethodOrderer, using names to help mitigate issues. Still, I wonder if JUnit will run classes in parallel because at least within the same class, order seems to work fine. Other classes don't require UI, which is good. Maybe I can avoid the headless property by catching with a timeout, but I’m not so sure. I'll edit the annotations to clarify things!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0d2b5657fa412a260169f63d30804481918db1c2ce60199445\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp9j0-UGxnpKuJ6kCKjMlPtmYLxPYX3OYPxwEvZibxrk21cC6mex5Z2E9dfIxyMw9C2jZWZ3dnqcvsiNoHKEdezhcAHmDhL3MjuLNQAPnADK7JGeI5L7gjslDWShwMFSgXMW2ON8XpQ0lM5_3sdLuOzG5q41IYhDdhB7FaVGexBzTJp8fBaGvVUZVmE1sLtqhM0STY4x4SYQLoHinR5IvGnXWDPXlzGDv9mv2r4PLJUUiq81k1xgMMAZx30xu0vvzmZkYXjp6evApjxjBhHVJKor7YEvB_rds13wsvBW1wXa3g0wku7L13j8MWlB1rkdS5OkWYX4WgSLD6iaudp-_WpbQE0fZC8JQ4GHH1rdOiEC7KatVt4-OeSdcMSa2eVylm0Vhj28LxVdQC1Pw0xnHFY1nvJVjQR5iUs3msdSDlQ2ICWQEd8OicGR2nDqmsOruli_2PFwvlSDnIdNYNW-ME-QJGhHZM1C6Vdv4pvRmST63G1Ryd1gABIINy1rPNLG8W320LMhPC-uJ33KR1kLcm43ybn7MDPiMsy5jOFnnRuFKWiVK_5BkW5rZpbYd2zQvjo3jRw1tZBrw1v9p3OZfx9b2CizIFaWo6ZoBCbIkFKEh2gmnlABO9T-ocLySJiXOsbzha0m2iXy9u-P73EeFPmDum-vacgka64Q5WVt8BmWJu7eIPbuqH6ovrw7CzZpvOSLaegaPgNefENFbrft8hYueDaQge6AP3JtGtwFekom_9lSXQ74hD1onXw30a9YeGfk3XCOpkChZX_trmwvrzdS4HZ4Yi1DFGQyQ4zDQKkoujOdNaf-OY96vxdzhLMfxER73FeM5oLeApJCskZJF4K3VfXmAWkxLviAsPcKXzelkHOqSIw7GC6fQT4rRZcYt4okV5XQefztycyyM9d8ozAf2CFb_fbAMxZvXWsHlANrWrClbROO0T-SoTtxDWK00FBYXeq0pEUSdVByORPWQO3cGA8ls7FtFPbf8v0WD7qu_ssP9N70AVmVRBA6J8qK3j6EeDsQY8azCmqEQoEa-g8Tx8gH5IAygxX90J5l-YDbWY0Zoe-7lTlWyqgO5TuNSwU0D_wtRwrzaFhiKVok6baO8XDihsbxe6EyE6AnFwtWpVlRKrkMRHbXtJKcv7pEPcsRqta4VxIeVnK6KgrwHQmhNazltC61IS2aIeFayl5hPQoqKyXSYgnXFB6f4bEnmKV4wrdbsnX_hBhBatTLZV6umL9-4JW3xGKYuuza54TLmaTh6L1U-p5JDNzdYLTpMqbeUcDYXoRCHldnO6VU-pIrudIRtDhYBDuEJQTdavRJoDbI2mcRtKPGnCIq8fV577QVZtNGyOq30ldCcYheQ8CiMMf0rrS98PQhdGhz_55jhW4YTvgmKXudXDiChc6oGMi1bv8X_yVcavKdQ3D9Tqsd2aS2K-ERXdD42Z1OMChXb2oH857BMfLkz_tQfOjdrI-ez1rpXg8g2GP5--FLs1UnYBaT5w