making the rerun test independent of headless settings by using Unsafe to allocate private fields, but that doesn’t seem ideal since direct reflection is forbidden and Unsafe is not great. I wonder if I could use `java.awt.GraphicsEnvironment.isHeadless()`, but that feel like an assumption I can’t skip. There’s also the idea of catching AWTError during the rerun test, particularly if it verifies unsupported cases. If JUnit executes tests in a random order, that could cause issues with the headless setting sticking around.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Addressing headless issues**\\n\\nI'm realizing that restoring the property won't reset the cached headless state, which means a later JFrame could still throw a HeadlessException. Since test order isn't guaranteed, I need to avoid setting the global headless to true. Instead, I guess I could configure the `createTestCollector` to throw a controlled exception after `newInstance`, but before the dialog appears. Unfortunately, I can't do that with `SimpleTestCollector`. So maybe I should create a custom TestCollector that sets a flag and returns an empty collection in `collectTests`.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering order execution**\\n\\nI’m thinking about the order of execution in my tests. I need to incorporate Order, TestMethodOrder, and MethodOrderer, using names to help mitigate issues. Still, I wonder if JUnit will run classes in parallel because at least within the same class, order seems to work fine. Other classes don't require UI, which is good. Maybe I can avoid the headless property by catching with a timeout, but I’m not so sure. I'll edit the annotations to clarify things!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_q5zIezf0RY0pDe7THFf2PfDk|fc_0d2b5657fa412a260169f63d3ef7048191b6162112bf065380", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/junit/junit/3.7/src/test/java/legacy/junit3/JunitSwinguiTestRunnerTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import org.junit.jupiter.api.Tes